article.description: Tamicha Jackson had 14 points, seven assists and a career-high seven rebounds and Jackie Stiles -- playing as a reserve for just the second time in her career -- added 11 points as the Fire beat the Minnesota Lynx 59-51 on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Fire warm up from 3-point range in home win
article.linkText: Fire finally get hot from long range, top Lynx
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- The Portland Fire got production from some
unusual sources Tuesday night.

	   Tamicha Jackson had 14 points, seven assists and a career-high
seven rebounds and Jackie Stiles -- playing as a reserve for just
the second time in her career -- added 11 points as the Fire beat
the Minnesota Lynx 59-51 on Tuesday night.

	   Alisa Burras added eight points and six assists for the Fire
(4-5), who won for the fourth time in five games and snapped a
five-game losing streak against Minnesota. Portland, the worst
3-point shooting team in the league, was 6-of-13 on 3-pointers,
easily its best percentage this year.

	   It's a new role for Stiles, who said after the game she had
never come off the bench before Saturday's game against Detroit.
She saw her first action since missing four games with bursitis in
her right heel.

	   "I just want to do whatever is possible to help the team win,''
Stiles said. "If my role is to come off the bench, then I'm happy
doing that. I don't want to mess with the chemistry we've got
during this winning streak.''

	   Said Portland coach Linda Hargrove: "Jackie is the kind of
player who is happy with whatever you want her to do. If you feel
like you need her coming off the bench, then that's what she'll
want to do.

	   "She's a coach's dream because she doesn't have this big ego.
Whatever role we decide is best for her, she's fine with it.''

	   Katie Smith led the Lynx (4-5) with 13 points, while Shaunzinski
Gortman added 10. Svetlana Abrosimova, the fifth-leading scorer in
the WNBA, was held to just five points on 1-for-13 shooting.

	   Trailing by one point at halftime, Minnesota went scoreless for
the first 4:44 of the second half and fell behind by 10.

	   "I thought we got outplayed,'' Lynx coach Brian Agler said.
"It looked like we weren't prepared, but we spent a lot of time
preparing for this game.''

	   The Lynx used an 8-2 run to get within 49-46, but Portland
quickly extended its lead back to double digits and kept Minnesota
at bay the rest of the way.

	   The Fire scored the game's first seven points and led 15-4.
Minnesota climbed back into the game with a 9-0 run, only to fall
behind by 11 again when Jackson scored four of her 10 first-half
points during a 6-0 run.

	   Following a timeout, the Lynx closed the half with an 11-0 run
to make it 32-31.

	   "No game that Minnesota ever plays is free-flowing, because
they won't let you play like that,'' Hargrove said. "I thought we
really rose to the challenge and we played as ugly as they did and
we won at their kind of game. It says a lot about the character of
our team.''

	   Sylvia Crawley had another mediocre effort one game after being
held scoreless for the first time in her WNBA career. Crawley was
just 3-of-10 for six points and five rebounds, and spent the last
several minutes of the game on the bench.
